=E2=80=8B=3D w,</strong></b><span> then there is an edge from vertex i havi=
ng weight w</span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"properties-of-adjacency-matrix" style=
=3D"text-align:left"><span>Properties of Adjacency Matrix</span></h2><ul><l=
i value=3D"1"><b><strong>Diagonal Entries</strong></b><span>: The diagonal =
entries A[i][j] are usually set to 0 (in case of unweighted) and INF in cas=
e of weighted, assuming the graph has no self-loops.</span></li><li value=
=3D"2"><b><strong>Undirected Graphs</strong></b><span>: For undirected grap=
hs, the adjacency matrix is symmetric. This means A[i][j] =E2=80=8B=3D A[j]=
[i]=E2=80=8B for all i and j.</span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"applications-of-adj=
acency-matrix" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Applications of Adjacency Ma=
trix:</span></h2><ul><li value=3D"1"><b><strong>Graph Representation</stron=
g></b><span>: The adjacency matrix is one of the most common ways to repres=
ent a graph computationally.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><b><strong>Connecti=
vity</strong></b><span>: By examining the entries of the adjacency matrix, =
one can determine whether the graph is connected or not. If the graph is un=
directed, it is connected if and only if the corresponding adjacency matrix=
 is irreducible (i.e., there is a path between every pair of vertices). In =
directed graphs, connectivity can be analyzed using concepts like strongly =
connected components.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><b><strong>Degree of Verti=
ces</strong></b><span>: The degree of a vertex in a graph is the number of =
edges incident to it. In an undirected graph, the degree of a vertex can be=
 calculated by summing the entries in the corresponding row (or column) of =
the adjacency matrix. In a directed graph, the in-degree and out-degree of =
a vertex can be similarly determined.</span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"advantages-=
of-adjacency-matrix" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Advantages of Adjacenc=
y Matrix:</span></h2><ul><li value=3D"1"><b><strong>Simple: </strong></b><s=
pan>Simple and Easy to implement.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><b><strong>Spa=
ce Efficient for Dense Graphs: </strong></b><span>Space efficient when the =
graph is dense as it requires V * V space to represent the entire graph.</s=
pan></li><li value=3D"3"><b><strong>Faster access to Edges: </strong></b><s=
pan>Adjacency Matrix allows constant look up to check whether there exists =
an edge between a pair of vertices.</span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"disadvantages=
-of-adjacency-matrix" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Disadvantages of Adja=
cency Matrix:</span></h2><ul><li value=3D"1"><b><strong>Space inefficient f=
or Sparse Graphs: </strong></b><span>Takes up O(V* V) space even if the gra=
ph is sparse.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><b><strong>Costly Insertions and D=
eletions: </strong></b><span>Adding or deleting a vertex can be costly as i=
t requires resizing the matrix.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><b><strong>Slow =
Traversals: </strong></b><span>Graph traversals like DFS, BFS takes O(V * V=
) time to visit all the vertices whereas Adjacency List takes only O(V + E)=
.</span></li></ul>                               =20
